SECTION 5: CONNECTIONS ANALYSIS (Trainer/Jockey)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

ELITE TRAINER COLONY (Fair Grounds 2024-2025):
───────────────────────────────────────────────

TIER 1 - CHAMPIONSHIP BARNS (20%+ Win Rate):
• Brad Cox: Elite national trainer, dominant in Derby preps and allowance races
  Pattern: Cox horses in stakes = serious intent; strong layoff pattern
• Steve Asmussen: Hall of Fame trainer, Fair Grounds powerhouse, massive stable
  Pattern: High volume; excellent with 2YOs and 3YO Derby preps; claims aggressively
• Al Stall Jr.: Louisiana-based Hall of Famer, local circuit specialist
  Pattern: Excels in claiming ranks; horses-for-courses expert
• Tom Amoss: Long-time Fair Grounds leader, consistent across all levels
  Pattern: Strong with claimers and allowance horses; excellent off layoffs

TIER 2 - TOP BARNS (15-20% Win Rate):
• Mark Casse: Elite trainer, ships quality for Derby preps
• Dallas Stewart: Solid Kentucky-based barn, Fair Grounds regular
• Ron Faucheux: Louisiana specialist, strong with turf runners
• Brendan Walsh: Improving barn, good with 3YOs
• Mike Maker: Turf specialist when shipping to Fair Grounds
• Norm Casse: Consistent, particularly strong with maiden graduates

TIER 3 - SOLID PROFESSIONALS (12-15% Win Rate):
• Various regional trainers with steady records
• Evaluate based on specific class levels and situations

TIER 4 - LIMITED/LOWER PERCENTAGE (<12% Win Rate):
• Approach with caution except in weak maiden/claiming races

TRAINER PATTERN ANALYSIS:
─────────────────────────

[TRAINER-1] ASMUSSEN CLAIM-AND-IMPROVE
Trigger: Steve Asmussen claimed horse in last start
Action: ADD +8 to +12 points to projected figure
Rationale: Asmussen claim = instant improvement via medication/training changes
Pattern: One of most reliable patterns in all of racing
Timeline: Enhancement strongest in first 2 starts post-claim

[TRAINER-2] COX/CASSE DERBY PREP PATTERN
Trigger: Elite 3YO trainer (Cox, Casse) entering Derby prep stakes
Action: Major confidence boost; expect sharp horse
Pattern: These barns target specific Fair Grounds races for Derby path
Verification: Check work pattern (should show strong recent works)

[TRAINER-3] STALL/AMOSS LOCAL CIRCUIT MASTERY
Trigger: Al Stall Jr. or Tom Amoss in claiming/allowance races
Action: ADD +3 to +5 points (local knowledge advantage)
Pattern: These trainers excel in Louisiana circuit; know track/surface intimately
Note: Particularly valuable in off-track conditions (they know how surface plays)

[TRAINER-4] FIRST-TIME STARTER (FTS) PATTERN
High-Percentage FTS Trainers at Fair Grounds:
• Steve Asmussen: ~18-20% FTS win rate (high volume)
• Brad Cox: ~22-25% FTS win rate (selective)
• Mark Casse: ~20-23% FTS win rate
• Tom Amoss: ~15-18% FTS win rate

Action: Upgrade FTS from these barns with strong work patterns
Requirements: Minimum 3 works, including bullet or strong recent 5F work

[TRAINER-5] LAYOFF SPECIALIST IDENTIFICATION
Trainers Excelling Off Layoffs:
• Brad Cox: Exceptional fresh; layoffs often strategic
• Tom Amoss: Strong pattern returning horses
• Steve Asmussen: Volume operation but handles layoffs well

Action: When these trainers return horse from 90+ days, reduce typical layoff penalty by 50%

[TRAINER-6] TURF SPECIALIST PATTERNS
Primary Turf Trainers at Fair Grounds:
• Mike Maker: National turf specialist
• Ron Faucheux: Louisiana-based turf expert
• Norm Casse: Solid turf record

Action: When these trainers switch horse to turf first time, positive indicator

ELITE JOCKEY COLONY (Fair Grounds 2024-2025):
──────────────────────────────────────────────

TIER 1 - CHAMPIONSHIP RIDERS (18%+ Win Rate):
• Joel Rosario: Elite national jockey, ships in for stakes and major mounts
  Strengths: Exceptional tactical rider, strong finisher, versatile
  Pattern: When Rosario at Fair Grounds, usually on live horse in stakes
• Florent Geroux: Based in Kentucky/Louisiana, consistent leader
  Strengths: Excellent pace judgment, strong with Cox/Asmussen barns
  Pattern: High win % across all levels; reliable in stakes and claiming
• James Graham: Consistent top rider, versatile
  Strengths: Good tactical speed management, reliable
• Colby Hernandez: Louisiana-based, high-percentage rider
  Strengths: Local circuit knowledge, strong gate speed

TIER 2 - SOLID PROFESSIONALS (15-18% Win Rate):
• Mitchell Murrill: Improving younger rider, good opportunities
• Diego Saenz: Solid journeyman, effective in claiming races
• Gerard Melancon: Veteran Louisiana rider, consistent
• Shane Bridgmohan: Experienced, particularly good on closers
• Adam Beschizza: Solid all-around rider

TIER 3 - ADEQUATE (10-15% Win Rate):
• Various journeymen riders
• Functional in appropriate spots

TIER 4 - APPRENTICE/LIMITED (<10% Win Rate):
• Avoid on favorites in competitive races
• May be acceptable in weak maiden/claiming races

[JOCKEY-1] RIDER UPGRADE SIGNAL
Trigger: Switch FROM Tier 3/4 TO Tier 1/2 jockey
Action: Major positive indicator (strong confidence boost)
Rationale: Barns secure top riders when expecting competitive effort
Pattern: Combined with equipment change = maximum intent signal

[JOCKEY-2] ROSARIO APPEARANCE PATTERN
When Joel Rosario ships to Fair Grounds (doesn't regularly ride there):
Action: Extreme positive signal (top national jockey shipped in specifically)
Pattern: Rosario at FG usually means elite barn with serious Derby prep or stakes horse
Verification: Check connections (likely Cox, Asmussen, Casse, or major shipper)

[JOCKEY-3] GEROUX/ASMUSSEN COMBINATION
Trigger: Florent Geroux riding for Steve Asmussen
Action: Strong positive indicator (preferred combination)
Pattern: High win % when paired; Geroux gets Asmussen's best mounts regularly

[JOCKEY-4] STAKES RIDER HIERARCHY
For graded stakes races:
• Tier 1 jockeys (Rosario, Geroux) receive majority of live mounts
• If a lesser jockey gets stakes mount from elite barn, investigate:
  - May indicate horse not meant to win (experience/exposure trip)
  - Or jockey has specific successful history with horse

[JOCKEY-5] APPRENTICE EVALUATION
Bug Weight Allowances: 5 lbs (*), 7 lbs (**), 10 lbs (†)
Fair Grounds Pattern:
• 5 lb bugs: Acceptable if showing competence (75+ mounts, 12%+ win rate)
• 7-10 lb bugs: Generally avoid on favorites (Fair Grounds track tricky)
Exception: Specific talented bugs with strong connections (evaluate individually)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 6: SURFACE CONDITIONS EXPERTISE (CRITICAL)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

NEW ORLEANS WEATHER REALITY:
────────────────────────────
Fair Grounds experiences significant rainfall during winter/spring meet. Off-track conditions occur 30-40% of racing days. Mastering off-track handicapping is ESSENTIAL for Fair Grounds success.

SURFACE CONDITION DEFINITIONS:
───────────────────────────────

FAST (FT):
• Dry, normal racing surface
• Standard handicapping applies
• All figure adjustments and bias patterns as documented

SEALED (SY):
• Track harrowed, rolled, and packed (preventative maintenance)
• Creates HARDER, FASTER surface than normal
• Often done anticipating rain or after light rain
• INCREASES speed bias significantly
Impact:
  • Speed horses run FASTER times than typical
  • Closers even more disadvantaged
  • Inside posts become more critical
Action: ADD +5 to +8 points to inside speed horses; DEDUCT -5 to -8 from closers

SLOPPY (SL):
• Surface water present, firm base underneath
• Water creates slick top layer but track drains well
• Often ENHANCES speed bias (slick surface helps early speed)
Impact:
  • Speed horses can maintain momentum
  • Kickback factor increases (inside closers compromised)
  • Times often fast despite "off" designation
Action: ADD +5 to +10 points to proven speed horses
Pattern: "Sloppy fast" phenomenon - horses run good times

MUDDY (MY):
• Deep saturation, water absorbed into surface
• Creates TIRING, energy-sapping surface
• Requires specific "mudders" (horses proven in mud)
Impact:
  • Speed advantage REDUCED (deep surface tires front-runners)
  • Proven mudders crucial (breeding + past mud form)
  • Times significantly slower than fast track
  • Pace dynamics shift (contested pace less damaging)
Action:
  • DEMAND proven mud form (check past performances)
  • Discount fast-track figures by -12 to -18 points
  • Breeding: Check for "mudder" sires/dams
  • Closers gain viability IF proven in mud

HEAVY (HY):
• Severely saturated, deepest condition
• Extremely tiring surface
• Rare at Fair Grounds (excellent drainage) but possible
Impact:
  • Only proven mudders competitive
  • Figure analysis largely irrelevant
  • Must have MULTIPLE strong muddy/heavy performances
Action: ONLY bet horses with proven heavy track form

GOOD (GD) - Turf Only:
• Slightly soft turf
• Normal turf racing condition
• Standard turf handicapping applies

YIELDING (YL) - Turf Only:
• Soft turf, holding surface
• Favors horses with proven soft-turf form
• European imports often excel
Action: Check past performances for soft/yielding turf success

SOFT (SF) - Turf Only:
• Very soft turf
• Requires specific soft-ground specialists
• Often races moved to dirt if this severe

MUDDER IDENTIFICATION:
──────────────────────

How to Identify Proven Mudders:
1. Past Performance Review:
   • Check for races on "Muddy" or "Sloppy" tracks
   • Look for competitive efforts (top 3 finishes)
   • Multiple mud races with success = proven

2. Breeding Analysis:
   Mudder Sire Lines:
   • Mr. Prospector line (historically good mudders)
   • Storm Cat line
   • Seattle Slew line
   • Distorted Humor, Lemon Drop Kid
   
   Dam Side: Look for mud winners in first two dams

3. Running Style:
   • Front-runners often better in mud (control pace)
   • Closers need to prove mud proficiency (harder to close in deep surface)

[SURFACE-1] OFF-TRACK MANDATORY CHECKS
When track listed as Sloppy, Muddy, or Heavy:
1. Review EVERY horse's past performances for off-track races
2. Eliminate horses with NO proven off-track form (unless breeding exceptional)
3. Upgrade horses with MULTIPLE strong off-track performances
4. Check breeding if no off-track races (mudder pedigree acceptable substitute)

[SURFACE-2] SEALED TRACK SPEED ADVANTAGE
When track sealed:
• Inside speed advantage AMPLIFIED
• Add +5 to +8 points to Posts 1-4 with early speed
• Closers: Avoid unless 15+ point figure edge + contested pace

[SURFACE-3] SLOPPY VS. MUDDY DISTINCTION
Critical to understand difference:
• SLOPPY: Often fast times, speed holds, kickback factor HIGH
  → Bet inside speed aggressively
• MUDDY: Slow times, tiring surface, mudders essential
  → Bet proven mudders only; breeding important

Check program or track announcements for surface designation; makes massive difference.

[SURFACE-4] INTRA-CARD SURFACE CHANGES
Fair Grounds surface can change race-to-race:
• Track listed "Sloppy" early, may dry to "Fast" by Race 6-7
• Monitor real-time updates if possible
• Early races = trust surface designation
• Later races = surface may have improved

Action: Be flexible; if track drying, closers gain viability in later races

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 7: WORKOUT ANALYSIS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

FAIR GROUNDS WORKOUT EVALUATION:
─────────────────────────────────
Fair Grounds maintains training track and main track for workouts. Work times must be evaluated in context of surface.

WORKOUT EVALUATION CRITERIA:
────────────────────────────

RECENCY:
• 0-5 days: Razor sharp, optimal
• 6-7 days: Sharp, standard
• 8-10 days: Acceptable
• 11-14 days: Slightly off peak
• 15+ days: Concern unless specific trainer pattern

DISTANCE:
Sprint Preparation: 4F-5F works optimal
Route Preparation: 5F-6F works, with at least one 5F+ in recent pattern
Derby Prep: Often see 6F-7F "big work" 10-14 days before race

QUALITY INDICATORS:
• "Bullet" (best work of day): Strong positive
• Handily (H): Standard positive work
• Breezing (B): Maintenance work
• Driving (D): Strong urging (evaluate context)

WORK SURFACE:
• Main Track: Standard for dirt horses
• Training Track: Generally slower; adjust expectations
Note: Fair Grounds training track often softer than main; expect slower times

WORK TIME ANALYSIS:
4F Work Evaluation (from gate):
• :47-:47.4: Exceptional (bullet territory)
• :48-:49: Strong work
• :50-:51: Adequate
• :52+: Moderate (context-dependent)

5F Work Evaluation:
• :59-1:00: Exceptional
• 1:01-1:02: Strong
• 1:03-1:04: Adequate
• 1:05+: Moderate

Training Track Adjustment: Add 1-2 seconds to above standards

FREQUENCY PATTERN:
• 1 work per 7-10 days: Standard maintenance
• 2-3 works per 2 weeks: Aggressive training (building fitness)
• 4+ works in 3 weeks: Intensive training (may indicate need for tightening)

[WORKOUT-1] DERBY PREP WORK PATTERN
For 3YO horses in Derby prep races:
Ideal Pattern:
• 3-4 works over 4-5 weeks
• Progressive improvement in work times
• Final work: 5F-6F "big work" 7-14 days before race
• "Bullet" or strong work as final prep = confidence signal

Elite Barns (Cox, Asmussen, Casse): Often work horses privately or at Churchill/Keeneland; published works may not reflect full preparation

[WORKOUT-2] MAIDEN/FIRST-TIME STARTER
For FTS horses:
Minimum Requirements:
• 3+ published works
• At least 1 work within 7 days
• Prefer 4F-5F bullet work
• Distance-appropriate preparation (5F work for route)

Elite Barn Allowance: Asmussen/Cox can win with minimal work tab if quality evident

[WORKOUT-3] LAYOFF WORK PATTERN
Horse returning from 90+ days:
Ideal Pattern: 4-5 works over 6-8 weeks showing progression
• Early: Slower, building fitness (1:03-1:04 for 5F)
• Middle: Sharpening (1:01-1:02 for 5F)
• Final: Sharp work (:59-1:00 for 5F)

Red Flag: Single work or very limited tab suggests horse needs race for fitness

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 8: PEDIGREE & BREEDING ANALYSIS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

WHEN PEDIGREE CRITICAL:
────────────────────────
1. Maiden races (no performance record)
2. First-time distance (especially routes)
3. First-time turf
4. 2-year-old races
5. Derby prep evaluation (stamina/class breeding)
6. OFF-TRACK CONDITIONS (mudder breeding)

DERBY PREP PEDIGREE:
────────────────────
Classic Distance Pedigree (1-1/8 mile - Louisiana Derby):
Essential Traits:
• Stamina influence (Tapit, Curlin, Empire Maker)
• Class influence (proven sires of classic winners)
• Two-turn routing ability

Red Flag Pedigrees:
• Pure sprint breeding (Speightstown, etc.)
• Lack of stamina in first two dams
• No routes winners in immediate family

MUD/OFF-TRACK PEDIGREE:
───────────────────────
Given Fair Grounds' frequent off-tracks, mud breeding CRITICAL:

Strong Mudder Sire Lines:
• Mr. Prospector descendants
• Storm Cat line
• A.P. Indy line
• Seattle Slew descendants
• Distorted Humor
• Lemon Drop Kid
• Smart Strike
• Malibu Moon (wet track)

Dam Side: Look for mud/wet track winners in first two dams

TURF PEDIGREE:
──────────────
Strong Turf Indicators:
• European sires (Galileo, Dubawi, etc.)
• Kitten's Joy, English Channel
• War Front, More Than Ready (turf crosses)
• Medaglia d'Oro (turf influence)

[PEDIGREE-1] OFF-TRACK BREEDING SUBSTITUTE
When horse has NO off-track racing experience but track is muddy:
Action: Strong mudder pedigree (sire + dam) acceptable substitute
Pattern: Young horses (2YOs, lightly-raced 3YOs) with mudder breeding often debut successfully in mud

[PEDIGREE-2] DERBY STAMINA EVALUATION
For Louisiana Derby and other route preps:
Action: Evaluate pedigree for stamina:
• Strong: Tapit, Curlin, quality routing sires = positive
• Weak: Pure sprint breeding = major concern for classic distance

[PEDIGREE-3] FIRST-TIME TURF
When horse attempting turf first time:
Action: Evaluate turf pedigree:
• Strong turf influence both sides = positive (+4-6 points)
• Mixed pedigree = neutral
• Dirt-only pedigree = caution

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 9: TRIP HANDICAPPING & RACE READING
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

TROUBLED TRIP IDENTIFICATION:
──────────────────────────────
• "Bumped start" / "Broke slowly"
• "Checked" / "Steadied"
• "Wide trip" (especially routes)
• "No room" / "Blocked"
• "Bore out/in" / "Lugged"
• "Altered course" / "Carried wide"
• "Shuffled back"
• "Caught inside" (closers trapped behind kickback)

TRIP EXCUSE VALIDATION:
Legitimate Excuse:
• Trouble at critical juncture (turn, stretch drive)
• Cost measurable ground/momentum
• Horse showed willingness before/after
• Finish doesn't reflect actual performance

Invalid Excuse:
• Early trouble, recovered, then weakened (form issue)
• Pattern of "bad trips" (likely horse characteristic)

Action: ADD +4 to +6 points when legitimate trouble validates

POSITIVE TRIP NOTES:
• "Saved ground" (routes)
• "Rail trip"
• "Improved position"
• "Showed gameness"
• "Strong late" (closer advancing)

FAIR GROUNDS-SPECIFIC TRIP FACTORS:
────────────────────────────────────
• Two-turn routes: Inside trip massive advantage (ground-saving)
• Sprints: Clean break essential (horses breaking poorly rarely recover due to speed bias)
• Off-track: Horses trapped inside behind kickback severely compromised
• Sharp turns: Wide trips very costly (tight one-mile oval)

[TRIP-1] KICKBACK COMPROMISE (Off-Track)
Trigger: Closer drew inside post (1-3) on sloppy/muddy track
Action: ADD +5 to +8 points if horse suffered kickback but finished competitively
Pattern: Indicates horse has ability; better post/surface today = strong play

[TRIP-2] WIDE TRIP ROUTES
Trigger: Horse traveled 4+ paths wide in route race
Action: ADD +4 to +6 points for ground loss
Calculation: Each path wide ≈ 1-1.5 lengths at Fair Grounds (tight turns)

[TRIP-3] PERFECT TRIP DISCOUNT
Trigger: Horse received ideal setup (uncontested lead, rail save, perfect pace)
Action: DEDUCT -4 to -6 points (trip unlikely to repeat)
Pattern: Lone speed inside post winners often overbet next time

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 10: WAGERING STRATEGY & VALUE IDENTIFICATION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

FAIR GROUNDS WAGERING PHILOSOPHY:
──────────────────────────────────
• Speed bias creates favorite bias in sprints (inside speed often justified chalk)
• Value exists in route races (more honest pace scenarios)
• Off-track conditions create overlay opportunities (public unfamiliar with mudders)
• Derby prep races: Sharp odds (national audience betting)
• Louisiana circuit races: Local money; patterns exist

CONFIDENCE-BASED BETTING TIERS:
────────────────────────────────

★★★★★ MAXIMUM CONFIDENCE (5-Star)
Characteristics:
• Inside speed (Posts 1-4) in sprint
• Dominant figure edge (10+ points)
• Fast or Sealed track
• Elite connections (Asmussen, Cox)
• No pace pressure (lone speed)
• No significant concerns

Betting Strategy:
• WIN: 5-7% of bankroll (aggressive but justified at Fair Grounds)
• EXACTA: Key on top across board
• TRIFECTA: Key on top with ALL underneath if value permits
• MULTI-RACE: SINGLE with confidence

★★★★ HIGH CONFIDENCE (4-Star)
Characteristics:
• Strong figure edge (6-9 points)
• Favorable post/pace scenario
• Solid connections
• Minor concerns but overall compelling

Betting Strategy:
• WIN: 3-5% of bankroll
• EXACTA: Key on top with 3-4 underneath
• TRIFECTA: Key on top with depth
• MULTI-RACE: Primary selection (single if strong sequence)

★★★ MODERATE CONFIDENCE (3-Star)
Characteristics:
• Competitive figures (3-5 point edge)
• Acceptable scenario
• Multiple possible outcomes

Betting Strategy:
• WIN: 1-2% of bankroll (value-dependent)
• EXACTA: Include in multi-horse structures
• MULTI-RACE: Secondary selection (spread with primary)

★★ LOW CONFIDENCE (2-Star)
Characteristics:
• Marginal advantage
• Uncertain factors
• Must-complete situation

Betting Strategy:
• WIN: Pass (0.5% max if forced)
• EXACTA: Saver only
• MULTI-RACE: Depth selection

★ PASS (1-Star)
Betting Strategy: PASS entirely

FAIR GROUNDS-SPECIFIC STRATEGIES:
──────────────────────────────────

[WAGER-1] THE INSIDE SPEED SPRINT PLAY
When all factors align (inside post 1-4, speed horse, fast/sealed track, no pace pressure):
• This is THE highest-probability play in all Fair Grounds handicapping
• Even at low odds (2/5, 3/5), often justified
• Action: Strong win bet + key on top in exotics
Exception: Only avoid if horse has significant form/class concerns

[WAGER-2] ROUTE RACE VALUE HUNTING
Routes at Fair Grounds fairer than sprints:
• Closers viable with pace setup
• Outside posts less disadvantageous
• Form/class matters more than post/style
Strategy: Target value closers with class edge in routes

[WAGER-3] OFF-TRACK OVERLAY OPPORTUNITIES
When track muddy:
• Public often over-bets fast-track speed horses
• Proven mudders with breeding support often overlays
Strategy: Identify proven mudders at 4/1+ odds; strong value plays

[WAGER-4] DERBY PREP EXACTA/TRIFECTA SPREADS
Louisiana Derby, Risen Star, Lecomte:
• Deep, talented fields
• Sharp national betting (odds often accurate)
• Multiple quality horses
Strategy: Spread in exotics; don't over-invest in win bets on short-priced Derby preps

[WAGER-5] ASMUSSEN CLAIM IMMEDIATE FOLLOW-UP
When Asmussen claims horse:
• Horse's NEXT race is statistical goldmine
• Often overlay (public doesn't recognize pattern)
• Action: Strong win bet + key in exotics
Pattern: One of most reliable angles in Fair Grounds handicapping

EXOTIC WAGER CONSTRUCTION:
──────────────────────────

EXACTA:
Strategy 1: Inside Speed Key (Sprint)
• Posts 1-4 speed horse over 3-4 others
• Cost: $6-$8
• Use when inside speed dominant

Strategy 2: Route Spread
• Box 3-4 logical contenders
• Cost: $12-$24
• Use in fairer route races

TRIFECTA:
Strategy 1: Lone Speed Key (Sprint)
• Inside speed / 3-4 horses / 5-6 horses
• Cost: $30-$48 for $0.50
• Use when speed dominant

Strategy 2: Competitive Route
• 2-3 horses / 3-4 horses / 5-6 horses
• Cost: $45-$72 for $0.50

MULTI-RACE WAGERS:
──────────────────

PICK-3:
Strategy: Build around strongest inside speed plays
• Race with 5-star inside speed: SINGLE
• Competitive races: Spread 3-4 horses
Cost: $9-$16 for $1

PICK-4/PICK-5:
Strategy: Conservative with 1-2 singles maximum
• Single only 5-star inside speed on fast/sealed track
• Spread other races based on confidence

PICK-6 (Fair Grounds Signature Bet):
Strategy: Requires disciplined approach
• Mix of singles (1-2 max), doubles (2-3), triples (1-2)
• Target carryover days
• Budget: $50-$200 depending on bankroll

[VALUE-RULE] FAIR GROUNDS CHALK REALITY
Pattern: Fair Grounds sprint favorites win ~38-42% (higher than national average)
Analysis: Inside speed bias creates justified favorites
Strategy:
• Support inside speed favorites in sprints (often warranted)
• Seek value in routes (more competitive)
• Target off-track races (public over-bets fast-track speed)

[VALUE-RULE] VULNERABLE FAVORITE PATTERNS
Identify weaknesses:
• Outside post (7+) speed horse in sprint
• Closer favored in sprint on fast track
• Fast-track specialist in muddy conditions
• Recent perfect trip unlikely to repeat
• Bounce concern (career-best last)

